## 1. Raw → wiki

Two layers: **raw** (all locally-readable source material) and **the wiki** (you own it,
concept-organized). Extract is an automated importer of awkward sources into `raw/imports/`;
plain-text/code are read directly without an import step.

| Raw | Why awkward | Import? |
|-----|-------------|---------|
| Jira | remote (API) + ADF + attachments | **Yes** — `raw/imports/jira/<KEY>.md` (extract imports it) |
| Office / PDF docs | local but binary, needs conversion | **Yes** — `raw/imports/<hash8>/<name>.md` (converted text) |
| Plain-text docs (`.md`/`.txt`), source code | local, already text | **No** — the repo *is* the local raw; synthesize reads it directly |

So the wiki is synthesized from **two kinds of input**: imports of awkward raw (under
`raw/imports/`), and plain-text/code raw read directly (scoped by git diff). An import
stays **source-axis** (one per raw source); the moment it is organized by *concept* it
has become the wiki.

| Layer | Location | Who owns it | Mutable by you? |
|-------|----------|-------------|-----------------|
| **Raw sources** | live Jira + the git repos in `wiki.config.yaml` `sources` + `raw/` | the human / `scripts/check_for_changes.py` | **Never edit a raw source.** External repos are `git pull --ff-only`'d during a source scan (HEAD = watermark); the wiki repo and `raw/` are never pulled. |
| **Imports** (materialized awkward raw) | `raw/imports/` | the **extract** phase (importer) | Yes, but only via extract. Read-only to synthesize. Synthesize never writes raw; `raw/imports/` is extract-owned, the rest of `raw/` is human-owned. |
| **The wiki** | `wiki/` | the **synthesize** phase | Yes — built from imports + raw read directly. |
| **The schema** | this `CLAUDE.md` | human + you | Only by explicit agreement. |

**Raw sources are the source of truth. The wiki is the derived, compounding artifact.**
When in doubt, the raw source wins.

